# PRISMp - PRIsm SiMPlified

Tools for processing and analyzing PRISM (Parameter-elevation Relationships on Independent Slopes Model) climate data.

## 🌍 Overview

PRISMp provides a simplified interface for working with PRISM climate data, offering tools for data processing, analysis, and visualization of high-resolution climate information.

## ✨ Features

### Data Processing
- **📥 Data Download**: Automated download of PRISM climate datasets
- **🔄 Format Conversion**: Convert between NetCDF, CSV, and other formats
- **✂️ Spatial Subsetting**: Extract data for specific regions or bounding boxes
- **⏱️ Temporal Aggregation**: Aggregate data across time dimensions (daily → monthly → annual)

### Analysis Tools
- **📊 Statistical Analysis**: Calculate climate statistics and indices
- **📈 Trend Analysis**: Detect and analyze climate trends over time
- **🔍 Anomaly Detection**: Identify climate anomalies relative to historical baselines
- **🗺️ Spatial Analysis**: Geographic analysis and mapping utilities

### Visualization
- **🎨 Map Generation**: Create publication-quality climate maps
- **📉 Time Series Plots**: Visualize climate variables over time
- **📊 Statistical Charts**: Histograms, scatter plots, box plots
- **🌐 Interactive Visualizations**: Web-based interactive plots (optional)

## 🚀 Quick Start

### Installation

```bash
# Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/ch3nji4n/prismp.git
cd prismp

# Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

# Or install in development mode
pip install -e .
```

### Basic Usage

```python
import prismp

# Download PRISM data
data = prismp.download(
    variable="tmean",  # mean temperature
    date="2020-01-01",
    resolution="4km"
)

# Process the data
processed = prismp.process.subset(data, bbox=[-125, 24, -66, 50])  # Continental US

# Analyze trends
trend = prismp.analysis.calculate_trend(processed, variable="tmean")
print(f"Temperature trend: {trend} °C/decade")

# Create visualization
prismp.visualization.plot_map(processed.tmean, title="Mean Temperature Map")
```

